Consider the following program, which creates an alias of a method. My use case for this kind of design pattern were two different precision implementations of some floating point code (i.e. ``computeSingle`` and ``computeDouble``) as well as an alias for the default compile time precision of the application (i.e. ``computeFloat``).

```cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

struct Test { void foo() { printf("foo\n"); } };

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(test) {
    py::module m("test");
    py::class_<Test> tclass(m, "Test");

    tclass
        .def(py::init<>())
        .def("foo", &Test::foo);

    tclass.attr("bar") = tclass.attr("foo");

    return m.ptr();
}
```

Calling this from Python 3.x produces the following issue (Python 2.7 works without problems):

```pycon
Python 3.4.3 (v3.4.3:9b73f1c3e601, Feb 23 2015, 02:52:03)
[GCC 4.2.1 (Apple Inc. build 5666) (dot 3)] on darwin
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> import test
>>> t = test.Test()
>>> t.foo()
foo
>>> t.bar()
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
TypeError: foo(): incompatible function arguments. The following argument types are supported:
    1. (self: test.Test) -> None

Invoked with:
```

What specifically happens here is that the implicit ``self`` argument is dropped, which causes method resolution to fail. The root cause is ``PyInstanceMethod_New``, which seems to be really picky about the name of the attribute that does the function call.

So when creating an alias, this means that we would have to un-box the method from it's method wrapper, and re-box it with a different name. It wasn't clear to me how to do that in a transparent way, and whether that's a generally reasonable workaround. What's also weird is that this kind of behavior does not occur in native Python classes, where method aliases can be created without such problems.

